        <chapter xml:id="quiz-solutions">
            <title>Weekly Quiz Solutions</title>
            
            <handout xml:id="week-3-quiz">
                <title>Week 3 Quiz</title>
                
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>

                    <p>
                        The function <m>f(x) = x^4-4x^3-20x^2+96x</m> has one local minimum at <m>x=-3</m>. Use this information, synthetic division and factoring, and sign analysis of derivatives to determine intervals on which <m>f(x)</m> is increasing or decreasing.
                    </p>
                    <p>You should be able to do this without looking at a graph.</p>
                </paragraphs>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        We find intervals on which a function is increasing or decreasing by doing <term>sign analysis</term> on the first derivative. If we needed to find intervals on which the function is concave up or down, then we would do sign analysis on the second derivative. Our basic steps are:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Find <m>f'(x)</m> and factor it completely. For this step, we will use the fact <m>f(x)</m> has a minimum at <m>x=-3</m>.
                                    We know <m>f'(x)=0</m> at an extreme value (minimum), so <m>x+3</m> will be one factor. We can use synthetic division to find the other factors.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Find all <term>roots</term> of <m>f'(x)</m> by solving <m>f'(x)=0</m> and also points where <m>f'(x)</m> does not exist. These are called the <term>critical points</term> of <m>f(x)</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Make a sign chart number line for <m>f'(x)</m> by marking all of critical points of <m>f(x)</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Determine the sign of <m>f'(x)</m> by testing points inside each interval. Or find the sign on one interval and then use multiplicity of roots to determine the remaining signs.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Interpret the sign chart. For each positive sign, we say <m>f(x)</m> is <term>increasing on</term> the corresponding interval. For each negative sign, we say <m>f(x)</m> is <term>decreasing on</term> the corresponding interval.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                        Now let's do the work.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the derivative:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>f(x) \amp = x^4-4x^3-20x^2+96x</mrow>
                            <mrow> f'(x) \amp = 4x^3-12x^2-40x+96 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 4(x^3-3x^2-10x+24) </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Use the minimum at <m>x=-3</m> to know <m>f'(-3)=0</m> and synthetic division.
                    </p>
                    <tabular>
                        <row>
                            <cell>-3</cell>
                            <cell left="medium"> 1 </cell><cell> -3 </cell><cell> -10 </cell><cell> 24 </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell></cell>
                            <cell left="medium"> 0 </cell><cell> -3 </cell><cell> 18 </cell><cell> -24 </cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell></cell>
                            <cell top="medium"> 1 </cell><cell top="medium"> -6 </cell><cell top="medium"> 8 </cell><cell top="medium"> 0 </cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                    <p>
                        So <m>f'(x) = 4(x+3)(x^2-6x+8) = 4(x+3)(x-2)(x-4)</m>.
                        Our sign chart number line will have marks at three roots: <m>x=-3</m>, <m>x=2</m>, and <m>x=4</m>.
                        Each of these roots has multiplicity 1, so <m>f'(x)</m> changes sign at each point.
                        Choose <m>x &gt; 4</m>, such as <m>x=5</m> and discover <m>f'(x) = +</m>.
                        Using multiplicity or testing each interval, we soon complete our sign chart.
                    </p>
                    <image xml:id="wk-3-quiz-sign-chart" width="50%">
                        <shortdescription>Sign chart number line showing f prime has signs that are negative to the left of -3, positive between -3 and 2, negative between 2 and 4, and positive to the right of 4.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm]
                        \draw (-5,0) -- (6,0);
                        \draw (-3,-0.25) -- (-3,+0.25) node [pos=0, below] {-3} node [pos=1, above] {0};
                        \draw (2,-0.25) -- (2,+0.25) node [pos=0, below] {2} node [pos=1, above] {0};
                        \draw (4,-0.25) -- (4,+0.25) node [pos=0, below] {4} node [pos=1, above] {0};
                        \node [above] at (-4,0.25) {$-$};
                        \node [above] at (-0.5,0.25) {$+$};
                        \node [above] at (3,0.25) {$-$};
                        \node [above] at (5,0.25) {$+$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    <p>
                        We are now ready to interpret the sign chart.
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p><m>f(x)</m> is <term>increasing on</term> the intervals <m>[-3,2]</m> and <m>[4,\infty)</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p><m>f(x)</m> is <term>decreasing on</term> the intervals <m>(-\infty,-3]</m> and <m>[2,4]</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        It is common to just talk about the open intervals, so that the endpoints are not included on either side, and that is what I would accept. However, the most correct interpretation is to include every endpoint at which the original function <m>f(x)</m> is continuous.
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>

            <handout>
                <title>Week 4 Quiz</title>
                
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>
                    <p>
                        The function <m>f(x)</m> is a <term>power function</term> that passes through the points <m>(1,12)</m> and <m>(8,3)</m>.
                        <ol>
                            <li><p>Find <m>f(x)</m></p></li>
                            <li><p>Use derivative sign analysis to determine intervals on which <m>f(x)</m> is increasing or decreasing</p></li>
                            <li><p>Use derivative sign analysis to determine intervals on which <m>f(x)</m> is concave up or concave down</p></li>
                            <li><p>Sketch a graph of <m>f(x)</m>.</p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Because <m>f(x)</m> is a <term>power function</term>, we know <m>f(x) = A \cdot x^p</m> for constants <m>A</m> and <m>p</m>. We use the points to create equations for <m>A</m> and <m>p</m>.
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> (x,y) = (1, 12) \quad \Rightarrow \quad \amp 12 = A \cdot 1^p </mrow>
                                        <mrow> \amp 12 = A </mrow>
                                        <mrow> (x,y) = (8, 3) \quad \Rightarrow \quad \amp 3 = A \cdot 8^p </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    Since we know <m>A=12</m>, we substitute into the second equation
                                    <md> 3 = 12 \cdot 8^p </md>
                                    and then isolate <m>8^p</m> to get
                                    <md> 8^p = \frac{1}{4} </md>
                                    We now recognize that 8 and 4 are both powers of 2, <m>8=2^3</m> and <m>4 = 2^2</m> so that we can reach an equation where the exponents must match:
                                    <md> 
                                        <mrow> (2^3)^p = \frac{1}{2^2} </mrow>
                                        <mrow> 2^{3p} = 2^{-2} </mrow>
                                        <mrow> 3p = -2 </mrow>
                                        <mrow> p = \frac{-2}{3}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                                <p>We have found <m>f(x) = 12 x^{-2/3}</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Now that we know <m>f(x) = 12 x^{-2/3}</m>, we can find <m>f'(x)</m>:
                                    <md> f'(x) = 12 \cdot (\frac{-2}{3}) x^{-5/3} = -8 x^{-5/3} </md>
                                    The exponent is <term>negative</term>, so <m>f'(x)</m> is <term>undefined</term> at <m>x=0</m>.
                                    The root (cube root) is odd, so the domain includes both negative and positive values.
                                    The power is also odd, so the sign changes at <m>x=0</m>.
                                    We have
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><p>For <m>x &gt; 0</m>, we have <m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> (negative)</p></li>
                                        <li><p>For <m>x &lt; 0</m>, we have <m>f'(x) &gt; 0</m> (positive)</p></li>
                                    </ul>
                                    So <m>f(x)</m> is <term>increasing</term> on <m>(-\infty, 0)</m> and <term>decreasing</term> on <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    From <m>f'(x) = -8 x^{-5/3}</m>, we can compute <m>f''(x)</m>:
                                    <md> f''(x) = -8(\frac{-5}{3}) x^{-8/3} = \frac{40}{3} x^{-8/3} </md>
                                    We are still working with odd (cube) roots, and this time there is an even power, so the sign of <m>f''(x)</m> is the same on both intervals.
                                    For <m>x \ne 0</m> we have <m>f''(x) &gt; 0</m> (positive).
                                    So <m>f(x)</m> is <term>concave up</term> on <m>(-\infty, 0)</m> and on <m>(0,\infty)</m>. (It is not valid to combine these intervals because <m>f(x)</m> is not continuous at <m>x=0</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Key features you need in your graph:
                                    <ul>
                                        <li><p><m>f(x)</m> has a negative power, so there will be a <term>vertical asymptote</term> at <m>x=0</m> and a <term>horizontal asymptote</term> <m>y=0</m></p></li>
                                        <li><p>The left side of the graph on the interval <m>(-\infty,0)</m> is increasing and concave up, which has the shape of the bottom right quadrant of a circle</p></li>
                                        <li><p>The right side of the graph on the interval <m>(0, \infty)</m> is decreasing and concave up, which has the shape of the bottom left quadrant of a circle</p></li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                                <image width="50%">
                                    <shortdescription>Graph of f(x) showing increasing and concave up on the left to a vertical asymptote and then decreasing and concave up on the right coming back down to a horizontal asymptote</shortdescription>
                                    <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[
                                    domain=-8:8,
                                    samples=200,
                                    ymin=0,
                                    ymax=3,
                                    axis lines=middle,
                                    xlabel={$x$},
                                    ylabel={$y$},
                                    restrict y to domain=0:5,
                                    ]
                                    \addplot[
                                    thick,
                                    ] {1/((x^2)^(1/3))};
                                    \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>

            <handout>
                <title>Week 5 Quiz</title>

                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        The function <m>f(x)</m> is a rational function that when completely factored can be written
                        <md>f(x) = \frac{3(x+2)^2(x-1)(x-3)}{2(x-1)^3(x-3)}</md>
                        <ol>
                            <li><p>Find the domain of <m>f(x)</m> and describe all discontinuities.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Compute the limit at each discontinuity. For any infinite limits, justify left- and right-sided limits clearly.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Determine <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to -\infty} f(x)</m>.</p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    A rational function's domain is all real numbers except for the roots of the denominator's polynomial. The factors of the denominator include <m>x-1</m> and <m>x-3</m>, so <m>f(x)</m> is undefined at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=3</m>. Written in interval notation, the domain is <m>(-\infty, 1) \cup (1,3) \cup (3,\infty)</m>.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    There are discontinuities at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=3</m>. We simplify the factors by cancelling any common factors:
                                    <md>f(x) = \frac{3(x+2)^2(x-1)(x-3)}{2(x-1)^3(x-3)} = \frac{3(x+2)^2}{2(x-1)^2}</md>
                                    In the simplified formula, only <m>x-1</m> remains as a denominator's factor. So <m>x=3</m> is a <term>removable discontinuity</term> while <m>x=1</m> is an infinite discontinuity (vertical asymptote).
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    We need to find limits for each discontinuity.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    At the removable discontinuity, we just use the simplified formula. The new formula is continuous so that we can just evaluate using the x-value.
                                    <md>
                                        \lim_{x \to 3} f(x) = \lim_{x \to 3} \frac{3(x+2)^2}{2(x-1)^2} = \frac{3(5)^2}{2(2)^2} = \frac{75}{8}
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    At the infinite discontinuity, the one-sided limits are infinite. We use sign analysis to determine whether the limits are <m>+\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m>. Because the simplified formulas has multiplicity 2 for each formula factor, the function never changes signs and is positive on each interval.
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> \lim_{x \to 1^-} f(x) = +\infty </mrow>
                                        <mrow> \lim_{x \to 1^+} f(x) = +\infty </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    Because the one-sided limits are the same, we write
                                    <md>\lim_{x \to 1^-} f(x) = +\infty </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    To find the limit at infinity, we need to know the highest power terms from the numerator and denominator. We don't actually need to multiply out all of the terms. Each factor will contribute a single power of <m>x</m>, so the numerator's leading term using the simplified formula will be <m>3x^2</m> and the denominator's leading term will be <m>2x^2</m>. Thus, for limits at infinity, we have:
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\lim_{x \to -\infty} f(x) \amp = \lim_{x \to -\infty} \frac{3x^2}{2x^2}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> \amp = \lim_{x \to -\infty} \frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> \amp = \frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>

            <handout>
                <title>Week 6 Quiz</title>

                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        Use the natural logarithm <m>\ln(\cdot)</m> to solve the equation
                        <md>
                            5 \cdot 2^{2x-1} = 25
                        </md>.
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>

                    <p>
                        We start by isolating the exponential term <m>2^{2x-1}</m>, dividing both sides of the equation by 5.
                        <md>
                            <mrow>5 \cdot 2^{2x-1} \amp = 25 </mrow>
                            <mrow>2^{2x-1} \amp = 5 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        We now apply the logarithm to both sides of the equation, so that we can use the power rule for logarithms:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\ln(2^{2x-1}) \amp = \ln(5) </mrow>
                            <mrow>(2x-1) \cdot \ln(2) \amp = \ln(5) </mrow>
                        </md>
                        We then proceed to isolate the <m>x</m>, first by dividing by <m>\ln(2)</m>, then adding 1, and finally dividing by 2:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>2x-1 \amp = \frac{\ln(5)}{\ln(2)} </mrow>
                            <mrow>2x \amp = \frac{\ln(5)}{\ln(2)} + 1 </mrow>
                            <mrow>x \amp = \frac{\frac{\ln(5)}{\ln(2)} + 1}{2} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>
            <handout>
                <title>Week 7 Quiz</title>
                
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        For <m>\displaystyle f(x) = \frac{x^2}{e^{x^2}}</m>, solve for all values <m>x</m> where <m>f'(x) = 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>

                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        First, we need to find the derivative. We could use the quotient rule directly.
                        <md>
                            <mrow>f'(x) \amp = \frac{d}{dx}\Big[ \frac{x^2}{e^{x^2}}\Big] </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{2x \cdot e^{x^2} - x^2 \cdot (2x e^{x^2})}{(e^{x^2})^2} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{e^{x^2} \cdot (2x  - 2x^3 )}{(e^{x^2})^2} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{2x  - 2x^3 }{e^{x^2}} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Alternatively, we could first rewrite this as a product and then take a derivative.
                        <md>
                            <mrow>f'(x) \amp = \frac{d}{dx}\Big[ x^2 e^{-x^2}\Big] </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = 2x \cdot e^{-x^2} + x^2 \cdot (-2x e^{-x^2}) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = e^{-x^2} \cdot (2x - 2x^3) </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Once we have the derivative, we solve for <m>f'(x)=0</m> by considering the factors.
                        We know that <m>e^{x^2}</m> or <m>e^{-x^2}</m> will always be positive and can never equal zero.
                        We just need to solve <m>2x-2x^3 = 0</m>, which we do by factoring:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>2x - 2x^3 \amp = 2x(1-x^2) = 2x(1-x)(1+x) = 0 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Considering each factor separately, we find three values: <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=-1</m>.
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>
            <handout>
              <title>Week 8 Quiz</title>
              
              <paragraphs>
                <title>Question</title>
                
                <p>
                  Expand <m>f(x)</m> as much as possible using logarithm properties and then compute <m>f'(x)</m>.
                  <md>
                    f(x) = \ln\Big(\left | \frac{4e^{x^2} (2x+3)^5}{x^3(x^2-5)^4} \right | \Big)
                  </md>
                </p>
              </paragraphs>

              <paragraphs>
                <title>Solution</title>
                
                <p>
                    The product rule of logarithms converts a logarithm of a product of factors
                    to the sum of the logarithms of each factor separately.
                    The quotient rule of logarithms does a similar item to division by a product of factors
                    so that the logarithm of each factor in the denominator is subtracted.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In the numerator, we need to recognize that <m>4e^{x^2}</m> has two factors.
                    So the factors in the numerator are <m>4</m>, <m>e^{x^2}</m>, and <m>(2x+3)^5</m>.
                    The factors in the denominator are <m>x^3</m> and <m>(x^2-5)^4</m>.
                    Using the product and quotient rules, we thus find
                    <md>
                        f(x) = \ln(4) + \ln(e^{x^2}) + \ln\big(|(2x+3)^5|\big) - \ln(|x^3|) - \ln\big((x^2-5)^4\big)
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Next we will use the power rule of logarithms
                    <md>
                        \ln(|u^p|) = p \ln(|u|)
                    </md>
                    and the inverse property of logarithms with exponentials
                    <md>
                        \ln(e^u) = u.
                    </md>
                    The result is that we now have a fully expanded formula:
                    <md>
                        f(x) = \ln(4) + x^2 + 5\ln\big(|2x+3|\big) - 3 \ln(|x|) - 4 \ln\big(|x^2-5|\big).
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The last step is to compute the derivatives.
                    <md>
                        <mrow> f'(x) \amp = 2x + 5 \cdot \frac{2}{2x+3} - 3 \cdot \frac{1}{x} - 4 \cdot \frac{2x}{x^2-5}. </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = 2x + \frac{10}{2x+3} - \frac{3}{x} - \frac{8x}{x^2-5}. </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
              </paragraphs>
            </handout>

            <handout><title>Week 9 Quiz</title>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        There is an angle <m>\theta</m> in standard position that intersects the unit circle
                        in the second quadrant with <m>\sin(\theta) = \frac{3}{4}</m>.
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>Draw a unit circle illustrating the terminal edge of the angle <m>\theta</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Show two different possible rotations that end at the terminal edge.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Find <m>\cos(\theta)</m>, <m>\tan(\theta)</m>, <m>\cot(\theta)</m> and <m>\sec(\theta)</m>.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        We start by drawing a unit circle with the x- and y-axes passing through the center.
                        We are told that <m>\sin(\theta)=\frac{3}{4}</m>, so the y-coordinate on the circle is <m>y=\frac{3}{4}</m>.
                        We mark that point on the y-axis.
                        We are also told to use the second quadrant, so we identify the point in that quadrant with the given y-coordinate.
                        We then draw a ray from <m>(0,0)</m> through that point and on to infinity.
                        Angles are illustrated by starting on the positive x-axis and rotating until we reach that ray.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The following figure illustrates the key ideas.
                    </p>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <shortdescription>Preliminary drawing of a unit circle with axes, showing a ray extending from the origin toward the second quadrant
                            that intersects the circle at a y-coordinate of 3/4.
                            Rotations are illustrated going from the positive x-axis in a positive (counter-clockwise) direction
                            and in a negative (clockwise) direction.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]

                            % Axes
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-1.2,0) -- (1.2,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-1.2) -- (0,1.2) node[above] {$y$};

                            % Unit circle
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1);
                            \draw[thick] (-0.05,0.75) -- (0.05, 0.75) node [right] {$\frac{3}{4}$};

                            % Ray endpoint
                            \coordinate (R) at (-1,{3/sqrt(7)});

                            % Ray from origin
                            \draw[-&gt;, blue,thick] (0,0) -- (R);
                            % Blue point and label
                            \filldraw[blue] ({-sqrt(7)/4}, {3/4}) circle (0.02)
                            node[left] {$\left(\hbox{?},\,\frac{3}{4}\right)$};

                            % Compute angle of my ray (degrees)
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rayangle}{atan2(3/sqrt(7),-1)}

                            % Counterclockwise arc, r = 0.25
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick, orange]
                                (0.25,0)
                                arc[start angle=0, end angle=\rayangle, radius=0.25];

                            % Clockwise arc, r = 0.35
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick, red]
                                (0.35,0)
                                arc[start angle=0, end angle=\rayangle-360, radius=0.35];

                            \draw[thick, purple, -&gt;]
                            plot[
                                variable=\t,
                                domain=0:{(360 + \rayangle)/360},
                                samples=200
                            ]
                            ({(0.45 + 0.04*\t)*cos(360*\t)},{(0.45 + 0.04*\t)*sin(360*\t)});

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    <p>
                        To find the other information, we will start with the equation of the unit circle (or the Pythagorean identity).
                        We know that <m>x^2+y^2 = 1</m> (unit circle), and that <m>y=\frac{3}{4}</m>.
                        <md>
                            <mrow> x^2 + (\frac{3}{4})^2 = 1 </mrow>
                            <mrow> x^2 = 1 - \frac{9}{16} </mrow>
                            <mrow> x^2 = \frac{7}{16} </mrow>
                            <mrow> x = \pm \frac{\sqrt{7}}{4} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Because we are in the second quadrant, we choose <m>x</m> to be negative.
                        Our figure can be updated now.
                    </p>
                    <image width="70%">
                        <shortdescription>Drawing of a unit circle with axes, showing a ray extending from the origin toward the second quadrant
                            that intersects the circle at a y-coordinate of 3/4.
                            Rotations are illustrated going from the positive x-axis in a positive (counter-clockwise) direction
                            and in a negative (clockwise) direction.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]

                            % Axes
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-1.2,0) -- (1.2,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-1.2) -- (0,1.2) node[above] {$y$};

                            % Unit circle
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1);
                            \draw[thick] (-0.05,0.75) -- (0.05, 0.75) node [right] {$\frac{3}{4}$};

                            % Ray endpoint
                            \coordinate (R) at (-1,{3/sqrt(7)});

                            % Ray from origin
                            \draw[-&gt;, blue,thick] (0,0) -- (R);
                            % Blue point and label
                            \filldraw[blue] ({-sqrt(7)/4}, {3/4}) circle (0.02)
                            node[left] {$\left(-\frac{\sqrt{7}}{4},\,\frac{3}{4}\right)$};

                            % Compute angle of my ray (degrees)
                            \pgfmathsetmacro{\rayangle}{atan2(3/sqrt(7),-1)}

                            % Counterclockwise arc, r = 0.25
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick, orange]
                                (0.25,0)
                                arc[start angle=0, end angle=\rayangle, radius=0.25];

                            % Clockwise arc, r = 0.35
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick, red]
                                (0.35,0)
                                arc[start angle=0, end angle=\rayangle-360, radius=0.35];

                            \draw[thick, purple, -&gt;]
                            plot[
                                variable=\t,
                                domain=0:{(360 + \rayangle)/360},
                                samples=200
                            ]
                            ({(0.45 + 0.04*\t)*cos(360*\t)},{(0.45 + 0.04*\t)*sin(360*\t)});
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    <p>
                        To find the other trigonometric functions, we use their definitions.
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \tan(\theta) \amp = \frac{\sin(\theta)}{\cos(\theta)} 
                                = \frac{(\frac{3}{4})}{(\frac{-\sqrt{7}}{4})}
                                = \frac{(\frac{3}{4})\cdot 4}{(\frac{-\sqrt{7}}{4})\cdot 4}
                                 = \frac{-3}{\sqrt{7}}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \cot(\theta) \amp = \frac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin(\theta)} = \frac{1}{\tan(\theta)} 
                                = \frac{-\sqrt{7}}{3}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \sec(\theta) \amp = \frac{1}{\cos(\theta)} 
                                = \frac{-4}{\sqrt{7}}</mrow>
                        </md>
                        
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>

            <handout><title>Week 10 Quiz</title>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Question</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        There is an angle <m>\theta</m> so that <m>\sin(\theta) = \frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>\tan(\theta)</m> is negative.
                        Use the trigonometric sum identities
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\sin(\alpha + \beta) \amp = \sin(\alpha) \cos(\beta) + \cos(\alpha) \sin(\beta) </mrow>
                            <mrow>\cos(\alpha + \beta) \amp = \cos(\alpha) \cos(\beta) - \sin(\alpha) \sin(\beta) </mrow>
                        </md>
                        to find <m>\tan(\theta + \frac{\pi}{2})</m>.
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
                <paragraphs>
                    <title>Solution</title>
                    
                    <p>
                        The two angles that are added are <m>\theta</m> and <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
                        To use the identities, we will need to know both sine and cosine for each angle.
                        For the angle <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, this is the point <m>(0,1)</m> on the positive <m>y</m>-axis of the unit circle.
                        Consequently, we know <m>\cos(\frac{\pi}{2}) = 0</m> and <m>\sin(\frac{\pi}{2}) = 1</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For <m>\theta</m>, we already know <m>\sin(\theta) = \frac{2}{3}</m>.
                        We use the Pythagorean identity to find <m>\cos(\theta)</m>:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \sin^2(\theta) + \cos^2(\theta) = 1 </mrow>
                            <mrow> (\frac{2}{3})^2 + \cos^2(\theta) = 1 </mrow>
                            <mrow> \cos^2(\theta) = 1 - \frac{4}{9} = \frac{5}{9}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \cos(\theta) = \pm \frac{\sqrt{5}}{3}</mrow>
                        </md>
                        Because there are two choices for the sign, we need to use the extra fact <m>\tan(\theta)</m> is negative.
                        Since <m>\tan(\theta) = \frac{\sin(\theta)}{\cos(\theta)}</m> and <m>\sin(\theta)</m> was positive,
                        we must choose <m>\cos(\theta) = - \frac{\sqrt{5}}{3}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We can now find separately <m>\sin(\theta + \frac \pi 2)</m> and <m>\cos(\theta + \frac \pi 2)</m>.
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \sin(\theta + \frac \pi 2) \amp = \sin(\theta) \cos(\frac \pi 2) + \cos(\theta) \sin(\frac \pi 2)</mrow>
                            <mrow>  \amp = \frac{2}{3} \cdot 0 + -\frac{\sqrt 5}{3} \cdot 1 </mrow>
                            <mrow>  \amp = -\frac{\sqrt 5}{3} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \cos(\theta + \frac \pi 2) \amp = \cos(\theta) \cos(\frac \pi 2) - \sin(\theta) \sin(\frac \pi 2)</mrow>
                            <mrow>  \amp = -\frac{\sqrt 5}{3} \cdot 0 - \frac{2}{3} \cdot 1 </mrow>
                            <mrow>  \amp = -\frac{2}{3} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        From this, we can find the tangent:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \tan(\theta + \frac \pi 2) \amp = \frac{\sin(\theta + \frac \pi 2)}{\cos(\theta + \frac \pi 2)} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{(\frac{-\sqrt{5}}{3})}{(\frac{-2}{3})} = 
                                (\frac{-\sqrt{5}}{3}) \cdot (\frac{-3}{2}) </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{5}}{2} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </paragraphs>
            </handout>
        </chapter>
    </book>
</pretext>